AC  GenProp0771
DE  Enterobactin (enterochelin) biosynthesis
TP  SYSTEM
AU  Haft DH
TH  0
CC  Enterobactin, also called enterochelin, is a catecholate siderophore
CC  found in most enterobacterial strains, where it may exist alongside
CC  other siderophore systems. It is a a cyclic trimeric lactone of
CC  N-(2,3-dihydroxybenzoyl)serine. The proteins EntA, EntB, and EntC
CC  produce 2,3-dihydroxybenzoate. Enterobactin synthetase is a
CC  non-ribosomal peptide synthase (NRPS) that builds enterobactin from
CC  three molecules of 2,3-dihydroxybenzoate and three of L-serine. The
CC  components of the enterobactin synthetase are designated EntB, EntE,
CC  and EntF. EntD is an accessory protein that phosphopantetheinylates
CC  EntB (PMID:9214294). EntH is a proofreading enzyme, a thioesterase,
CC  while EntS is a specific exporter across the plasma membrane.
**  Note that enterobactin is a triscatechol deriv. of a cyclic triserine
**  lactone. The closely related corynebactin (improperly renamed
**  bacillibactin) is a trithreonine derivative:
**  2,3-Dihydroxybenzoate-Glycine-Threonine Trimeric Ester, needs property,
**  look vicinity of NTL01BS3193 BCE_2400
--
